WEBVTT

00:02.850 --> 00:08.976
You are listening to a teaching from Reality LA.

00:08.996 --> 00:10.138
Morning church, great to see you.

00:10.298 --> 00:10.798
How you doing?

00:12.019 --> 00:12.380
Good.

00:12.700 --> 00:15.603
Well, we are in a sermon series right now that we're calling the essentials.

00:15.623 --> 00:22.130
We're doing this for four weeks where we want to talk about four essentials for healthy involvement in the church.

00:22.630 --> 00:29.938
And those are to gather on Sundays, engage our discipleship pathway, be involved in Christian community,

00:29.986 --> 00:32.149
and then serve in some capacity.

00:32.650 --> 00:35.915
And so today we're talking about being involved in Christian community.

00:36.236 --> 00:42.806
And to do that, we'll look at Colossians three versus 12 through 17, which is about how to experience real community.

00:43.748 --> 00:47.373
And while you're turning to Colossians three in your Bibles, let me tell you a quick story.

00:47.414 --> 00:50.258
My wife and I moved to LA in,

00:50.402 --> 01:00.722
2013, January 1st, and the first book that I read when I got to LA was on the road by Jack Kerouac.

01:00.834 --> 01:11.188
See, for three years before that, I'd been working on my dissertation and didn't have room to read anything outside of the one topic that I was focused on during that time.

01:11.769 --> 01:14.973
And so finally, once I had some space, I wanted to read fiction.

01:15.034 --> 01:18.839
I'd been wanting to read this book for a long time, and so I read On the Road.

01:19.139 --> 01:26.289
And it's a great story about several guys making a road trip across America in search of freedom, belonging, and purpose.

01:26.930 --> 01:29.874
And in the story, they come to Los Angeles.

01:29.922 --> 01:32.605
A city that's overflowing with people and activity.

01:33.185 --> 01:35.308
And yet, here's what Jack Kerouac says about it.

01:36.229 --> 01:39.472
L.A. is the loneliest and most brutal of American cities.

01:40.253 --> 01:45.899
New York gets god awful cold in the winter, but there's a feeling of wacky comrade ships somewhere in the streets.

01:46.519 --> 01:47.981
L.A. is a jungle.

01:49.483 --> 01:50.143
I'll tell you this.

01:50.584 --> 01:53.647
After living here for 13 years, I think that he's right.

01:54.087 --> 01:56.530
L.A. is a lonely place.

01:56.898 --> 01:58.220
And it's so ironic, isn't it?

01:58.260 --> 02:00.784
Because there are so many people here.

02:00.824 --> 02:04.689
And based on social media, it seems like they're all connected.

02:04.730 --> 02:12.080
Everyone's hiking together, running in Canyon, and waiting in long lines for overpriced coffee and silver lake together.

02:12.241 --> 02:16.527
And out on the streets for the Dodgers parade, there's so many people here.

02:16.587 --> 02:21.394
And yet, of course, social media doesn't always represent reality.

02:21.602 --> 02:24.752
Most people in this city are hurting and alone.

02:24.812 --> 02:30.850
And why is it that LA is such a lonely place, uniquely lonely?

02:31.211 --> 02:33.458
Well, I think there are at least three reasons.

02:33.922 --> 02:35.884
One is that the city is so transient.

02:36.405 --> 02:39.068
People are constantly coming and going.

02:39.088 --> 02:41.051
They come here for college and leave.

02:41.071 --> 02:43.214
They come here for a job and then eventually leave.

02:43.354 --> 02:47.739
It's a hard place to raise families so people get married and have kids and they leave.

02:48.080 --> 02:49.802
The entertainment industry is rough.

02:49.862 --> 02:51.083
It's been a hard several years.

02:51.244 --> 02:52.045
People leave.

02:52.385 --> 02:56.370
So it's a transient city and it's hard to build relationships and that.

02:56.418 --> 03:00.906
The second reason it's so lonely is that it's so sprawling.

03:01.687 --> 03:08.459
LA consists of 114 neighborhoods spread out over 500 square miles.

03:09.160 --> 03:19.378
So if you live in Culver City and you meet someone who lives in Pasadena, it's going to be hard to sustain a relationship when the city is just so spread out.

03:19.810 --> 03:25.676
So LA is lonely because it's transient, it's sprawling, and third because it's competitive.

03:25.696 --> 03:37.367
People here are driven, they have big dreams, and they learn to see others either as competitors who threaten their career or commodities who can help them in their career.

03:38.348 --> 03:45.795
And so relationships easily become transactional, networking replaces friendship, and people become means rather than ends.

03:46.696 --> 03:49.298
So LA is a lonely place.

03:49.538 --> 03:53.104
It's really hard to have genuine community here.

03:53.905 --> 03:57.611
And yet, as humans, we were made for community.

03:57.671 --> 04:01.818
And then as followers of Jesus, we especially value this.

04:02.799 --> 04:09.330
And so for us as a church, we did a survey where we asked people this question, do you have Christian friends

04:09.410 --> 04:13.534
that you regularly connect with for intentional Christian fellowship.

04:13.915 --> 04:16.277
And I was encouraged by the results overall with this.

04:16.297 --> 04:20.722
I mean, 76% of you said, yes, that you do have this and praise God.

04:20.762 --> 04:21.423
That's amazing.

04:21.443 --> 04:22.844
That's actually really encouraging.

04:23.505 --> 04:26.148
But then there's the 24% that said they don't.

04:26.788 --> 04:32.955
They don't have Christian relationships where they're regularly intentionally engaging with for fellowship.

04:33.035 --> 04:35.858
And we're talking about hundreds of people here.

04:36.130 --> 04:40.234
who say that they're trying to follow Jesus, but don't have that.

04:41.035 --> 04:47.581
And so today what I wanna do is I wanna talk to that 24% and invite you into community.

04:47.721 --> 04:55.668
And I wanna talk to the 76% as well and help define and deepen what you already have in Christian community.

04:56.869 --> 04:59.312
And so everybody wants community.

04:59.652 --> 05:01.013
I don't have to convince anyone of that.

05:01.134 --> 05:05.938
Everybody wants community, but not everyone wants to do what it takes to have real community.

05:06.370 --> 05:09.473
And Colossians chapter three is going to show us how to get there.

05:09.774 --> 05:17.662
It gets beyond superficial connection and it shows us what real community is like and then it gives us some tools to be able to experience it.

05:18.283 --> 05:22.047
So let me read this passage for us and then I'll pray that God would speak to us through it.

05:22.588 --> 05:26.171
Colossians chapter three, verses 12 through 17.

05:26.211 --> 05:35.922
Put on then, as God's chosen ones, holy and beloved, compassionate hearts, kindness, humility,

05:36.002 --> 05:39.368
meekness and patience, bearing with one another.

05:39.408 --> 05:44.457
And if one has a complaint against another, forgiving each other as the Lord has forgiven you.

05:44.497 --> 05:46.360
So you also must forgive.

05:47.322 --> 05:58.802
And above all these, put on love, which binds everything together in perfect harmony and let the peace of Christ rule in your hearts to which indeed you were called in one body and be grateful.

05:59.426 --> 06:09.440
Let the word of Christ dwell in you richly, teaching and admonishing one another in all wisdom, singing Psalms and hymns and spiritual songs with thankfulness in your hearts to God.

06:10.161 --> 06:16.711
And whatever you do, and word or deed, do everything in the name of the Lord Jesus, giving thanks to God the Father through him.

06:17.292 --> 06:18.954
This is God's word, pray with me.

06:22.599 --> 06:27.346
God, we know that when we talk about LA as a lonely place, that we're not just talking about that in theory,

06:28.034 --> 06:31.698
but that many of us here today, that's our experience.

06:32.939 --> 06:42.250
That we don't feel like we have people that we can genuinely go to and just be vulnerable and raw and honest and wonder how they'll respond or not.

06:43.391 --> 06:47.535
And so God, we believe your word when you say that you set the lonely in family.

06:48.717 --> 06:53.342
We believe your word when you say that we were made for community and that we need community.

06:54.083 --> 06:57.106
But God, we need you to show us how that's possible.

06:57.570 --> 07:00.695
And we need you as a good shepherd to guide us into that.

07:01.616 --> 07:16.599
And so I pray, God, that we would lay down our preconceived notions or unrealistic expectations that we would have and that we would embrace real community that can be difficult and require sacrifice, but is worth it.

07:17.200 --> 07:18.682
We pray this all in your son's name.

07:19.323 --> 07:19.624
Amen.

07:20.545 --> 07:20.866
Amen.

07:21.707 --> 07:26.354
All right, well, I want to start off by talking about the enemy of real community.

07:26.434 --> 07:27.836
And it's not busyness.

07:28.617 --> 07:30.240
It's not personality differences.

07:30.300 --> 07:31.502
It's not even conflict.

07:32.143 --> 07:36.549
I believe that idealism is the enemy of real community.

07:37.431 --> 07:42.158
What happens is we have a dreamy version of community where it happens spontaneously.

07:42.478 --> 07:43.660
Everyone always gets along.

07:43.720 --> 07:46.524
No one disappoints and love feels effortless.

07:47.546 --> 07:55.538
We imagine community without conflict, belonging, without inconvenience, intimacy, without vulnerability and unity, without forgiveness.

07:56.226 --> 08:01.033
And when real people don't live up to that vision, then we quietly disengage.

08:02.155 --> 08:14.073
And some of you are in that place today and you think, well, I'd have community if there were more people my age or I'd have community if people lived closer to me or I'd have community if some of these people liked the same things that I like.

08:15.375 --> 08:21.985
And the unrealistic vision of community that we have keeps us from experiencing real community altogether.

08:23.407 --> 08:25.330
Well, my goal today

08:25.410 --> 08:28.853
is to take an axe to your idealistic vision of community.

08:30.175 --> 08:35.900
Sometimes as a preacher, I try to inspire, imagine the world renewed by the grace of God.

08:36.140 --> 08:38.542
Well, today I'm not trying to inspire you.

08:38.583 --> 08:42.326
In fact, I hope this might be my most uninspiring sermon ever.

08:43.667 --> 08:47.471
Because my goal today is to confront you with reality.

08:48.252 --> 08:54.898
Community is hard and sometimes horrible, and yet it's absolutely necessary and even beautiful.

08:55.330 --> 08:56.733
You have to have it.

08:57.013 --> 08:58.296
You have to have community.

08:58.837 --> 09:03.246
But to have it, you have to die to yourself over and over and over again.

09:03.266 --> 09:13.488
And what's so striking when we turn to Colossians 3 is that the Bible doesn't correct our expectations by offering us a more inspiring vision of community.

09:13.929 --> 09:16.594
It corrects them by being brutally honest.

09:17.282 --> 09:21.528
And when you read this passage in Colossians 3, one thing becomes immediately clear.

09:21.949 --> 09:25.474
Paul is not writing to people who are naturally getting along.

09:26.696 --> 09:36.891
Like why else would he write a letter to a church and say, you need to be compassionate, you need to be patient, you need to be more forgiving, you need to be, why would he say that?

09:37.292 --> 09:41.458
Because he's writing to people who have issues

09:41.666 --> 09:46.372
and have a hard time getting along together and are fighting with each other and then going at it.

09:46.573 --> 09:48.235
And so he's writing to them.

09:48.255 --> 09:52.561
Paul assumes that people are hard to live with.

09:53.062 --> 09:54.263
Conflict is inevitable.

09:54.564 --> 09:58.329
Forgiveness is required and love must be chosen constantly.

09:59.290 --> 10:02.194
I mean, I tell you, I was praying about what to preach on today.

10:02.626 --> 10:09.936
There were some other passages, like I, pardon me, we wanted to preach on John 13 where Jesus says, as I've loved you, loved one another, like that sounds beautiful.

10:09.976 --> 10:10.636
It's amazing.

10:10.657 --> 10:12.339
Like how is Jesus loved us, loved one another?

10:12.679 --> 10:14.121
But I was like, no, we need the grit.

10:15.022 --> 10:18.647
Like we need to know that this is hard.

10:18.947 --> 10:20.770
And that's what you have in this passage.

10:20.810 --> 10:22.893
I mean, it's talking about forgiveness.

10:22.953 --> 10:24.535
It's talking about bearing with one another.

10:24.575 --> 10:30.162
Paul is assuming these people are having a hard time with it because it's hard.

10:30.466 --> 10:38.016
because bringing sinners together who are works in progress and calling them to follow Jesus together is gonna create some friction.

10:38.076 --> 10:47.408
And so the way to genuine Christian community is not by avoiding conflict, but by walking through it in a Christ-like way together.

10:48.329 --> 10:55.719
In fact, it's the conflict followed by forgiveness and reconciliation and growing together that makes the relationship that much deeper.

10:55.759 --> 10:58.002
That is, if,

10:59.106 --> 11:00.409
you're willing to stick around for that.

11:01.832 --> 11:09.648
And I think there's three stages that people go through on their way towards genuine Christian community.

11:10.330 --> 11:12.274
The first is excitement.

11:12.450 --> 11:20.280
Imagine that you go to a community group and it's bustling and these people are doing life together and praying for each other and you're like, yes, this is it.

11:20.320 --> 11:23.445
I didn't know this existed and this is what I need right here in Los Angeles.

11:23.765 --> 11:25.407
This community group is amazing.

11:25.427 --> 11:26.469
These people are awesome.

11:27.450 --> 11:33.618
And then like two or three weeks in, you're like, but that one person has some interesting political views.

11:34.978 --> 11:39.024
And there's a few people who are a little bit socially awkward and it's getting weird.

11:39.044 --> 11:40.106
I'm not sure what to do.

11:40.286 --> 11:41.669
I don't know how to go about this.

11:42.229 --> 11:46.717
And then eventually maybe a couple of weeks later, somebody says something that offends you or hurts you.

11:47.778 --> 11:53.768
And so you go from stage one, excitement to stage two, which is disappointment.

11:53.788 --> 11:55.551
I go, these people aren't all that I thought they were.

11:55.611 --> 11:57.554
These people do make mistakes.

11:57.574 --> 11:58.395
They do mess up.

11:59.236 --> 12:01.540
And so you go from excitement to disappointment.

12:01.720 --> 12:02.802
And then here's the key.

12:03.106 --> 12:04.428
Here's the fork in the road.

12:04.688 --> 12:07.192
At this point, you can either say, I'm out.

12:08.173 --> 12:10.977
I don't wanna be around people who have different political views that I do.

12:10.997 --> 12:13.221
A person makes me awkward.

12:13.241 --> 12:14.362
I don't wanna deal with that.

12:15.404 --> 12:17.547
You can either, this is the fork in the road.

12:17.687 --> 12:19.830
You can either say, I'm gonna go find a different community.

12:19.850 --> 12:20.871
I'm gonna go to a different church.

12:20.891 --> 12:22.794
I'm gonna go to different relationships.

12:23.055 --> 12:31.026
You can either do that, or this is when you can commit and start experiencing real community.

12:31.874 --> 12:39.763
That's the process, excitement, disappointment, commitment that leads to genuine, authentic community.

12:40.904 --> 12:44.588
And I do want to give one qualification to everything that I'm saying here.

12:44.628 --> 12:49.173
I'm not telling anyone to stay in an abusive relationship or a toxic environment.

12:49.513 --> 12:50.374
Okay, that's not good.

12:50.915 --> 12:52.456
You need to have healthy boundaries in your life.

12:52.516 --> 12:54.158
You can do that and be a gracious person.

12:54.999 --> 13:01.266
And if you're not sure like, oh, is this just like hard and I need to fight through it and be committed or is this like,

13:01.474 --> 13:05.639
an unhealthy environment that I shouldn't stay in, talk to one of our elders.

13:05.679 --> 13:07.982
We'd love to talk through that and pray with you about that.

13:08.623 --> 13:12.347
So I'm not saying you have to stay in every relationship, every community.

13:12.748 --> 13:18.836
I am calling people to commit to real community that's messy, difficult, and takes time.

13:20.157 --> 13:24.082
And my concern is that lots of people have experienced,

13:24.162 --> 13:28.467
Lots of people haven't experienced their idealized version of community.

13:28.507 --> 13:34.674
And so they've settled instead for shallow digital connectedness or the buzz of a crowd.

13:36.055 --> 13:41.982
But here's the thing, you can have hundreds or even thousands of followers on social media and still be lonely.

13:43.063 --> 13:46.627
And being around people all the time doesn't do it either.

13:47.368 --> 13:52.914
Like if you're looking for easy surface level community or easy surface level unity,

13:53.058 --> 13:55.481
Go to a Taylor Swift concert or a Dodgers game.

13:55.581 --> 13:56.602
It'll feel amazing.

13:56.742 --> 14:00.106
Everyone will be doing like cheering for the same thing in the right direction.

14:00.166 --> 14:00.907
That's amazing.

14:01.247 --> 14:02.709
But that's not real community.

14:02.989 --> 14:03.650
That's a crowd.

14:04.671 --> 14:07.374
Those people aren't going to show up for you when you're in the hospital.

14:08.135 --> 14:11.178
Those people aren't going to come cry with you when you go through a difficult breakup.

14:11.779 --> 14:15.563
Those people are going to pray for you when your kids are struggling and you don't know what to do.

14:16.945 --> 14:18.246
We need real community.

14:19.368 --> 14:21.490
And some of you here today,

14:22.786 --> 14:26.853
You've given up on genuine community.

14:27.594 --> 14:29.116
And I want to talk to you for a second.

14:29.256 --> 14:33.163
If that's you, if you're here today and you're saying, I've tried, I can't do this anymore.

14:33.183 --> 14:34.024
It's too painful.

14:34.104 --> 14:35.506
I want to say to you, God loves you.

14:35.567 --> 14:37.390
He's for you.

14:37.450 --> 14:43.359
And your wounds from the past don't have to hold you back from relationships in the future.

14:44.621 --> 14:50.130
We are wounded in relationships, but we also can only experience healing in relationships.

14:50.690 --> 14:56.557
and they don't have to be the same relationships, but we were made for relationships and we need to experience healing.

14:56.577 --> 14:59.540
This is why this is part of our discipleship pathway.

14:59.580 --> 15:03.525
As followers of Jesus, we need to experience healing from our wounds.

15:04.646 --> 15:11.054
So if you're in that place, you've got to let go of unrealistic expectations and embrace the messiness of real community.

15:11.614 --> 15:12.696
Now is the time.

15:12.756 --> 15:14.397
Today is the day.

15:14.417 --> 15:18.322
If you're waiting for perfect community,

15:18.434 --> 15:20.739
then you'll never experience community at all.

15:23.346 --> 15:28.277
And so we've talked about how idealism is the real enemy of community.

15:28.317 --> 15:33.650
But now let's talk about how Jesus is the source of real community.

15:33.858 --> 15:41.113
And before we get to the nitty and gritty of this passage, you have to understand the logic of community in this letter that's called Colossians.

15:41.714 --> 15:49.170
So in the first two chapters in Colossians one and two, Paul gives us this massive cosmic gospel vision.

15:49.410 --> 15:52.835
Jesus is the image of the invisible God.

15:53.376 --> 15:59.025
He's the creator of all things, the sustainer of all things, the reconciler of all things.

15:59.085 --> 16:04.713
And through the cross, He's reconciled not only God and sinners, but heaven and earth.

16:05.394 --> 16:10.201
He died and rose from the grave, ascended to heaven where He's seated at the right hand of God.

16:10.302 --> 16:11.784
That's Colossians 1 and 2.

16:12.104 --> 16:18.514
Then you get to Colossians 3, and Paul brings that cosmic gospel down into everyday life.

16:19.266 --> 16:22.551
He says at the beginning of Colossians 3, you've been raised with Christ.

16:23.352 --> 16:28.199
And so put off the old self and put on the new self.

16:28.900 --> 16:30.903
So imagine work with the imagery here.

16:30.984 --> 16:38.775
He's saying your old self is like an old dirty shirt that's covered with stains and rips and tears.

16:38.855 --> 16:44.223
It represents your guilt, your shame, all the sin of your past.

16:44.904 --> 16:48.690
He's saying, take off the old self and then put

16:48.770 --> 16:51.173
on the new self that's in Christ.

16:51.213 --> 17:10.237
So you're taking off this old stained shirt and you're putting on a pure white spotless shirt that represents that you've been purified, you've been redeemed, you've been washed, you've been cleaned by Jesus Christ, you are putting on the new self.

17:10.938 --> 17:17.426
And so that's what he says, you've been raised with Christ, put off the old self, put on the new self, but you got to get this.

17:17.922 --> 17:23.769
when he talks about the new self and actually everything in this passage, he's not talking to us merely as individuals.

17:24.590 --> 17:26.632
This is all communal.

17:26.692 --> 17:29.576
That's the substructure of everything that's said here.

17:30.236 --> 17:32.659
I mean, this letter was written to a church.

17:33.540 --> 17:40.128
And then in this passage that we're looking at today, every time it says you, it's the second person plural.

17:40.428 --> 17:44.393
You all are as some of our friends say, y'all, okay?

17:44.793 --> 17:45.554
Everyone.

17:45.890 --> 17:49.195
This is not God's love letter to you as an individual.

17:49.916 --> 17:57.066
This is God's word to his community teaching us how to follow his son Jesus together.

17:57.567 --> 18:00.892
And so here's the thing, this is an amazing passage, Colossians chapter three.

18:01.372 --> 18:03.696
You cannot obey this passage by yourself.

18:04.197 --> 18:04.537
You can't.

18:05.318 --> 18:06.320
It's literally impossible.

18:07.161 --> 18:13.490
As we're gonna see, there are four one-on-others in this passage and you can't do those alone.

18:13.570 --> 18:18.136
Miley Cyrus can buy herself flowers, but she can't love one another by herself.

18:19.018 --> 18:19.899
Okay, you can't do it.

18:21.661 --> 18:27.229
And so this is all inherently communal and it's all by grace.

18:27.950 --> 18:33.217
We enter into this community not based on achievement, but by redemption.

18:34.559 --> 18:40.808
And what it's saying is that the gospel reconciles us to God and adopts us into a family.

18:41.930 --> 18:42.290
So,

18:42.946 --> 18:43.767
I have an older brother.

18:43.807 --> 18:54.363
And so that means that when I was born, I was born simultaneously as a son and a brother at the same time.

18:54.403 --> 18:56.827
That's always been my identity.

18:57.047 --> 19:01.834
I've never had identity outside of being a son and a brother.

19:02.715 --> 19:04.178
And the same thing is true for us.

19:05.199 --> 19:12.530
When we trust in Jesus and we are born again, we are simultaneously sons and daughters of God,

19:12.962 --> 19:15.125
and brothers and sisters of one another.

19:15.826 --> 19:16.407
We're family.

19:17.769 --> 19:22.235
And so this is crucial for understanding what Paul is doing here in Colossians chapter three.

19:22.976 --> 19:23.898
Look at verse 12 with me.

19:24.459 --> 19:30.788
He says, put on then as God's chosen ones, holy and beloved.

19:30.948 --> 19:31.629
Here's what he's doing.

19:32.330 --> 19:36.376
He's declaring their communal identity over them.

19:36.396 --> 19:37.938
And

19:38.210 --> 19:39.552
His word is living and active.

19:39.872 --> 19:43.296
He's declaring our identity over us.

19:44.337 --> 19:46.860
He's saying, you are chosen.

19:46.920 --> 19:48.322
What a beautiful truth.

19:49.203 --> 19:51.405
So often we worry about, will anyone accept me?

19:51.445 --> 19:52.366
Will anyone want me?

19:52.807 --> 19:55.090
We fear that we'll be rejected.

19:55.130 --> 19:58.073
God looks upon us and says, you're chosen.

19:58.113 --> 20:02.738
And he looks upon us and he declares, you're holy.

20:02.778 --> 20:05.842
Now I know that you might think, well, I don't feel very holy.

20:06.754 --> 20:07.815
I don't feel very pure.

20:07.855 --> 20:11.358
I don't feel set apart, but God is declaring this.

20:11.398 --> 20:13.320
This isn't an identity that you achieve.

20:13.380 --> 20:15.883
It's an identity that you receive through faith.

20:16.843 --> 20:18.045
God says, you're holy.

20:18.105 --> 20:21.388
You've been made holy by the blood of Jesus Christ.

20:22.028 --> 20:22.949
You've been forgiven.

20:22.989 --> 20:30.917
You've been washed so that when God looks at us, he doesn't see the accumulation of all of our shortcomings and our sin and our failure.

20:31.437 --> 20:33.239
He sees the righteousness of Jesus.

20:34.160 --> 20:35.000
You're chosen.

20:35.060 --> 20:36.722
You're holy.

20:37.154 --> 20:38.536
And he says, and you're beloved.

20:38.916 --> 20:39.817
You're my beloved.

20:40.358 --> 20:45.223
The beautiful God looks at us and he's just overwhelmed with love.

20:46.064 --> 20:51.450
He moves towards us in compassion and he wants you to know that's your identity.

20:51.751 --> 20:54.333
You are the beloved of God.

20:54.374 --> 21:01.842
And so he starts this passage out, Paul does, by declaring their identity over them.

21:02.402 --> 21:04.064
And this is how the gospel works.

21:04.104 --> 21:07.767
You receive an identity by faith and then you live that out.

21:08.768 --> 21:11.471
So you don't enter into community as a self-made person.

21:11.531 --> 21:16.275
You enter in as someone who's already loved, already forgiven and already secure.

21:17.076 --> 21:21.380
And that frees you from using community to justify yourself.

21:22.541 --> 21:31.410
Because if you don't already know that you're loved by God, then you'll ask community to give you what only God can, approval, validation and worth.

21:32.258 --> 21:36.544
And honestly, that's why so many different communities collapse.

21:36.564 --> 21:40.390
If a community is built on achievement, then it falls apart when we fail.

21:41.592 --> 21:44.536
If it's built on chemistry, then it fades when we change.

21:45.538 --> 21:51.166
Compatibility can create a community for a season, but only grace can sustain it over time.

21:52.608 --> 21:59.218
And so only a community centered on Jesus can become this kind of real community.

22:00.194 --> 22:03.221
Because only Jesus gives us an identity that's unshakeable.

22:03.923 --> 22:07.271
Only Jesus can hold together people who will let one another down.

22:07.311 --> 22:11.962
Only Jesus creates a family where we don't have to perform to belong.

22:12.022 --> 22:16.051
And this is who we are by grace.

22:17.234 --> 22:18.898
It's our communal identity.

22:19.842 --> 22:25.172
You know, I was in New York City in the fall and I was staying right outside of Central Park.

22:25.332 --> 22:29.861
So every morning when I was there, I would wake up and I would go run in Central Park.

22:30.342 --> 22:31.123
It's just amazing.

22:31.163 --> 22:31.804
It's beautiful.

22:31.844 --> 22:32.546
It's the fall.

22:32.586 --> 22:34.109
The leaves are changing colors.

22:34.890 --> 22:38.056
And I noticed something while I was running there every day.

22:38.096 --> 22:43.346
They had these signs everywhere that said, Central Park is your backyard.

22:44.226 --> 22:45.448
And I saw it first.

22:45.508 --> 22:46.729
I didn't think much about it.

22:46.749 --> 22:47.510
But then I saw it again.

22:47.530 --> 22:48.511
I kept seeing them.

22:49.232 --> 22:54.799
And I started noticing it kind of had an impact on me in the way that I was thinking about Central Park.

22:54.819 --> 22:55.520
Like here I am.

22:55.901 --> 22:58.384
I'm a visitor from Los Angeles coming to New York.

22:58.965 --> 23:02.049
Like this isn't like, I don't have any responsibility here.

23:02.249 --> 23:04.672
Like I'm just coming in and running through here because it's beautiful.

23:04.712 --> 23:06.354
It's a nice setting, right?

23:06.786 --> 23:11.797
But I kept reading the sign and genuinely, it shaped the way I viewed Central Park.

23:12.499 --> 23:13.601
And I started thinking about it.

23:13.621 --> 23:22.761
It's a brilliant marketing scheme because at the end of the day, what they're trying to do is to keep, to help people pick up their own trash.

23:23.783 --> 23:24.946
Like that's what they want.

23:25.186 --> 23:31.915
They want people to not trash Central Park, but to treat it well, pick up after yourselves, do things like that.

23:32.336 --> 23:40.968
But rather than putting a sign out that says, hey, idiot, pick up your own trash, they put a sign out that says Central Park is your backyard.

23:41.929 --> 23:45.394
They're saying, we have a mutual responsibility here.

23:45.714 --> 23:47.116
We're in this together.

23:47.176 --> 23:48.338
This is about us.

23:48.962 --> 23:51.987
And so what they were doing is that they were motivating by identity.

23:52.247 --> 23:54.971
I think they're taking a page out of God's book.

23:56.133 --> 24:01.261
He is trying to motivate his people by reminding them of their communal identity.

24:02.182 --> 24:07.370
Colossians three is a sign in the middle of our lives saying, the church is your family.

24:09.133 --> 24:10.355
These are brothers and sisters.

24:11.717 --> 24:12.899
These are people you use.

24:13.780 --> 24:16.284
These aren't people that you come and go with when it's convenient.

24:16.324 --> 24:17.586
The church is your family.

24:18.082 --> 24:19.544
He's saying, you are chosen.

24:20.004 --> 24:20.785
You are holy.

24:21.146 --> 24:22.327
You are beloved.

24:22.367 --> 24:26.292
And now you get to live in light of that.

24:27.975 --> 24:33.101
So I've tried to show you that idealism is the real enemy of community.

24:33.141 --> 24:40.811
And I hope that you give up on your idealistic visions of community, but real community is possible because of the good news of Jesus.

24:41.412 --> 24:46.418
And while it's glorious, it's messy, difficult and advances through hardship and conflict.

24:46.754 --> 24:48.998
So the question now is, how do we do it?

24:49.739 --> 24:55.428
I mean, hopefully I've got you convinced like, okay, I'll give up on these dreamy visions of community.

24:55.468 --> 24:56.609
I want real community.

24:56.950 --> 24:57.371
I get it.

24:57.411 --> 24:57.811
It's hard.

24:57.831 --> 24:58.793
I'm willing to sacrifice.

24:59.193 --> 25:00.135
How do I do it?

25:00.275 --> 25:00.976
What do I do?

25:01.036 --> 25:09.810
Well, for the rest of Colossians chapter three, it gives us four practices and seven postures.

25:10.050 --> 25:12.914
Okay, so I'm gonna walk through these rather briskly.

25:14.276 --> 25:18.102
First, four practices to cultivate real community.

25:19.164 --> 25:20.886
Four practices to cultivate real community.

25:20.906 --> 25:23.630
And the first is, bear with one another.

25:24.131 --> 25:24.592
I love this.

25:24.632 --> 25:27.676
In verse 13, it talks about bearing with one another.

25:27.716 --> 25:30.741
And this might be the key practice to the whole thing.

25:30.781 --> 25:39.474
The Greek word here for bearing means to endure patiently or to put up with or even to suffer.

25:40.034 --> 25:42.096
you're willing to suffer one another.

25:42.116 --> 25:49.785
And so this idea of bearing with one another, it assumes that people will irritate, disappoint, and frustrate you.

25:50.646 --> 25:54.010
It assumes that, but you have to give them grace.

25:54.130 --> 25:55.972
You have to bear with them.

25:56.873 --> 26:00.498
So let's try and get a little bit more concrete here, okay?

26:01.399 --> 26:05.804
Let me just tell you, the person sitting next to you is a piece of work, okay?

26:05.824 --> 26:07.826
Just a work in progress.

26:08.194 --> 26:09.916
Okay, I'm just trying to make this concrete.

26:10.376 --> 26:11.778
They're a work in progress.

26:12.839 --> 26:16.323
And listen, like they're going to have some ups and downs in life.

26:17.505 --> 26:21.029
And here's the thing though, you have to bear with them.

26:21.049 --> 26:22.330
You know why?

26:22.370 --> 26:25.294
Because you don't know everything that they've been through.

26:25.334 --> 26:27.616
You don't know their experiences.

26:27.636 --> 26:28.838
You don't know their past.

26:28.858 --> 26:32.722
You can see how they look, but you don't know what's going on in their hearts.

26:33.282 --> 26:34.964
So you gotta be patient with them.

26:34.984 --> 26:36.647
You gotta be gracious with them.

26:36.947 --> 26:38.269
You gotta endure with them.

26:38.289 --> 26:41.294
You gotta bear with them over time.

26:41.354 --> 26:48.865
Now, not only is that true about the person sitting next to you, but think about what they're thinking now, about their thinking about you.

26:48.905 --> 26:57.097
Now here on this question, when we talk about bearing with one another, okay?

26:59.681 --> 27:00.722
Most of you,

27:00.994 --> 27:06.041
probably almost all of you immediately think about you bearing with a difficult person.

27:07.263 --> 27:07.584
Okay?

27:08.044 --> 27:08.866
So how does this work?

27:08.886 --> 27:13.733
Does that mean like we're the lucky ones, we chose all the like people who don't cause problems here.

27:13.773 --> 27:17.338
And then we all know other people who cause probably who are like, we have to bear with.

27:18.119 --> 27:22.426
No, we all think about, oh, there's something, there's this difficult person that I've got to bear with.

27:22.946 --> 27:24.569
Here's the thing, you're the person too.

27:25.791 --> 27:26.812
You are the person too.

27:26.912 --> 27:30.898
You're sitting next to someone who was thinking, you're working progress.

27:31.202 --> 27:32.083
And that's the truth.

27:32.924 --> 27:36.488
You need people in your life who will bear with you.

27:37.489 --> 27:50.303
You need people who will in your life, who will give you the benefit of the doubt, who will be patient with you, who will be gracious towards you, who will respond with love when you are unloving.

27:50.343 --> 27:57.431
You need people to bear with you in your life and you need that for you to be able to be honest and vulnerable and open with other people.

27:58.092 --> 27:59.193
So look, we need each other.

27:59.233 --> 28:00.274
It's all of us.

28:01.026 --> 28:05.211
We need people to bear with us, and we need to bear with one another.

28:08.836 --> 28:11.679
There's a New Testament scholar from China.

28:11.739 --> 28:13.401
Her name is Shiyashiyashu.

28:14.042 --> 28:20.350
And she talks about how Christians in the West tend to think of unity as the absence of conflict.

28:21.271 --> 28:25.816
And so we seek unity and peace by the removal of all conflict.

28:25.836 --> 28:28.860
So when there is no conflict, then we have peace and unity.

28:29.501 --> 28:30.482
But she says that,

28:31.106 --> 28:38.755
Cultures in majority cultures and Christians all over the world, especially people who have experienced oppression, they think of this differently.

28:39.396 --> 28:45.884
She says that unity is not the absence of conflict, but a deeper agreement amidst the conflict.

28:46.865 --> 28:55.836
And here's what she says, the essence of the church is the community in union with Christ in the midst of conflict.

28:57.378 --> 29:00.722
It assumes conflict because we're broken people.

29:00.802 --> 29:01.763
in a broken world.

29:02.505 --> 29:08.494
And so the way to discover deeper unity is not by minimizing our differences, but magnifying our agreement in Jesus.

29:09.715 --> 29:10.857
Conflict is inevitable.

29:11.899 --> 29:17.667
And our goal is not to avoid conflict, but to let it lead us into deeper unity and peace.

29:17.687 --> 29:20.451
And to do that, we have to bear with one another.

29:21.233 --> 29:24.317
So it's the first practice to cultivate real community.

29:24.658 --> 29:27.161
The second is to forgive one another.

29:28.003 --> 29:30.226
You see this in verse 13.

29:30.338 --> 29:38.029
He says, bearing with one another, and if one has a complaint against another, forgiving each other as the Lord has forgiven you.

29:38.389 --> 29:40.732
So you also must forgive.

29:42.014 --> 29:55.232
So listen, if you're in community and someone wrongs you, whether they realize it or not, the right response is not to avoid it or even to minimize it or just to run away from it.

29:55.993 --> 29:59.378
No, it's to acknowledge it and to seek forgiveness.

30:01.154 --> 30:02.996
to acknowledge it and to seek forgiveness.

30:03.977 --> 30:14.669
And this is so important because for some of you, it's bitterness that is holding you back from experiencing real loving relationships in your life.

30:16.071 --> 30:25.682
And you are hurt at some point and you haven't dealt with that hurt and you haven't forgiven and that bitterness

30:26.274 --> 30:33.723
That hurt is turning into bitterness, which is flowing over into resentment, not only to the one person who hurt you, but to all people around you.

30:34.404 --> 30:39.550
And it's building a barrier around you where you're longing for deep relationships and you can't experience them.

30:40.291 --> 30:42.133
And the root of that is bitterness.

30:43.334 --> 30:44.796
And so you have to forgive.

30:45.657 --> 30:47.619
You have to be willing to let that go.

30:47.659 --> 30:50.002
And forgiveness doesn't mean saying it's all right.

30:51.202 --> 30:53.144
It wasn't okay if somebody hurt you.

30:53.544 --> 30:58.810
It's acknowledging that that was wrong and yet you're willing to let it go for the sake of relationship.

30:58.890 --> 31:00.992
I'm not going to hold this against someone anymore.

31:02.353 --> 31:04.916
And we often think, well, I need to forgive for their sake.

31:05.676 --> 31:07.919
Yeah, but you need to forgive for your sake as well.

31:08.779 --> 31:13.644
I mean, it's been said that not forgiving someone is like drinking poison and expecting the other person to die.

31:15.726 --> 31:16.287
It doesn't work.

31:16.847 --> 31:18.129
You have to let that go.

31:18.229 --> 31:19.570
You have to forgive.

31:20.322 --> 31:23.306
And some of you are saying, yeah, but you don't know how hard that is.

31:25.028 --> 31:26.971
But listen, this is the key in verse 13.

31:26.991 --> 31:31.016
It says, we forgive one another as the Lord has forgiven you.

31:31.437 --> 31:40.029
If you're only looking at that person's wrong doing, I understand why it can feel very difficult to forgive, even if that person won't acknowledge what they've done.

31:41.050 --> 31:50.002
But when you look to Christ and realized that you had sinned greatly against him and yet he forgave you, then

31:50.146 --> 31:51.928
you will be able to forgive others.

31:53.269 --> 31:54.030
And so we need this.

31:54.350 --> 31:55.851
I'm not just talking about individuals.

31:56.232 --> 32:06.261
We need a culture of forgiveness because if forgiveness isn't built into your community, it will only be a matter of time until your community collapses and fractures.

32:08.023 --> 32:15.050
And if you can't learn to do this, then you will just jump from community to community, from relationship to relationship.

32:15.790 --> 32:19.794
Every time you get hurt building up the wall a little bit more.

32:20.418 --> 32:21.820
So we have to bear with one another.

32:22.421 --> 32:23.883
We have to forgive one another.

32:24.844 --> 32:30.031
Third, the third practice to cultivate real community is teach one another.

32:31.052 --> 32:33.476
And this is discipleship.

32:34.377 --> 32:37.661
We're learning from one another about how to follow Jesus.

32:38.503 --> 32:39.784
We all have things that we don't know.

32:39.804 --> 32:44.050
We all have blind spots and we need each other to teach one another.

32:44.802 --> 32:48.907
And the key in this passage is that the teaching comes from the Word of God.

32:48.927 --> 32:54.153
It says, let the Word of Christ dwell in you richly teaching one another.

32:54.173 --> 32:55.394
And again, that you is plural.

32:55.815 --> 33:01.682
Let the Word of Christ dwell in you all richly teaching one another.

33:02.843 --> 33:06.728
So you might think, oh, I have financial questions.

33:06.828 --> 33:12.274
Well, great, maybe someone can come alongside of you and say, well, let's see what the Bible says about stewardship and generosity.

33:12.674 --> 33:14.481
Oh, you're struggling with singleness.

33:14.662 --> 33:16.850
Let's see what the Bible says about singleness.

33:17.513 --> 33:20.323
Oh, you're riddled with fear because of what's happening in our society.

33:20.665 --> 33:24.178
Let's see what the Bible says about fear and how we can live in light of it.

33:24.898 --> 33:28.263
So we have to teach one another from the scriptures.

33:28.323 --> 33:31.848
This doesn't mean setting up a pulpit in somebody's living room.

33:31.888 --> 33:43.305
It means constantly opening the word of God or memorizing the word of God or having a spirit put words of God in your heart that you can share with other people where you're teaching each other as we follow Jesus.

33:44.306 --> 33:46.930
And then the fourth practice that we need to cultivate

33:47.330 --> 33:50.475
real community is admonishing one another.

33:50.996 --> 33:54.842
Now, I know that the word admonish is not in most of your day to day vocabulary.

33:54.882 --> 33:56.324
So let me unpack this.

33:56.785 --> 34:05.319
Webster's dictionary defines admonish as to warn counsel or advise someone earnestly, often with the aim of correcting behavior or preventing harm.

34:06.240 --> 34:11.048
So basically to admonish someone is to lovingly warn or correct them for their good.

34:12.090 --> 34:12.370
And

34:12.898 --> 34:13.599
It's interesting.

34:13.659 --> 34:21.948
The Greek word behind admonish literally means to put something into someone's mind, to put something into someone's mind.

34:21.968 --> 34:34.461
So it's as if like someone's just living a certain way and, you know, maybe they're, they're drifting from God's will in some way or another and they just haven't, the thought hasn't even entered their mind.

34:35.362 --> 34:37.564
And you're willing to put that thought in their mind.

34:37.604 --> 34:39.506
Like, what does God say about this?

34:40.034 --> 34:48.686
Hey, like look at this truth from scripture and admonishing it shouldn't be at least it shouldn't be harsh or shaming.

34:49.247 --> 34:58.540
When Paul says admonish one another, he's talking about loving honest conversations where we care enough about someone's soul to speak the truth even when it's uncomfortable.

34:59.421 --> 35:02.585
And it assumes relationship, trust and humility.

35:04.107 --> 35:05.970
So I mean, I think back in my own life,

35:06.466 --> 35:23.524
I've been discipled by being taught things by lots of people proactively and some of the key discipleship moments in my life are when people loved me enough to bring hard truth in front of my eyes so that I could see what was going on in my own heart and so that I could change.

35:24.666 --> 35:26.227
And so we need that with each other.

35:28.109 --> 35:36.018
I know we're afraid of confrontation and coming across and this and that, but scripture tells us not only to do this, but it talks about how to do it.

35:36.322 --> 35:45.016
to speak the truth in love, to admonish one another, to admonish someone is to bring loving truth for them, not against them.

35:46.438 --> 35:55.271
And so we need to bear with one another, forgive one another, teach one another, and admonish one another.

35:56.714 --> 36:04.626
And you know, these are four of the one anothers in the scriptures, but they're actually 59 one anothers.

36:05.026 --> 36:06.808
throughout the New Testament, 59.

36:07.409 --> 36:10.533
It talks a lot about how we need one another.

36:10.553 --> 36:12.095
Let me just give you a sampling of these.

36:12.755 --> 36:26.252
Confess your sins to one another, pray for one another, honor one another, instruct one another, serve one another, bear one another's burdens, be patient with one another, and encourage one another.

36:27.573 --> 36:30.657
This is what it means to be the body of Christ.

36:31.798 --> 36:34.962
So let me ask you two really practical questions.

36:35.106 --> 36:38.511
Okay, because I hope that you're getting this, but I want you to apply it to your own life.

36:38.551 --> 36:39.172
Two questions.

36:39.934 --> 36:43.479
First is this, who do you do the one another's with?

36:45.122 --> 36:48.086
Who are the people in your life that you confess your sins to one another?

36:48.106 --> 36:48.888
You pray for one another.

36:48.908 --> 36:50.570
You encourage one another.

36:50.971 --> 36:52.113
You bear one another's burdens.

36:52.393 --> 36:54.677
Who are those people?

36:55.819 --> 37:03.090
You know, in our discipleship pathway, we talk about how important it is to be known in community.

37:03.458 --> 37:09.966
By that, what we mean is having a small group of people that you go deep with, that you go deep with, that you do the one and others.

37:10.627 --> 37:16.775
Like, we are a church community and this congregation, we can't do the one and all the one and others with each other.

37:17.876 --> 37:24.364
But what we can do is have deeper relationships that we're committed to throughout the week where we're actually doing those things.

37:25.225 --> 37:25.746
And so,

37:26.850 --> 37:31.275
The main way that we create structure for this in our church is through community groups.

37:32.036 --> 37:35.821
And community groups are a place where we welcome and love one another.

37:36.602 --> 37:37.483
It's a lonely city.

37:37.803 --> 37:41.087
We want to welcome people in and that we want to love one another.

37:42.108 --> 37:48.957
By sharing life, by speaking truth to each other, to meeting one another's needs, by praying for one another.

37:49.457 --> 37:51.079
That's what our community groups are about.

37:51.700 --> 37:56.626
And one of the reasons that are the

37:56.738 --> 38:02.506
The statistic that I showed you that we have a lot of people in Christian communities because of community groups.

38:02.526 --> 38:04.869
I'm just so encouraged hearing stories about this.

38:04.889 --> 38:09.516
I mean, I heard someone a while ago said to me, I wouldn't even be in LA anymore if it weren't for my community group.

38:10.357 --> 38:14.683
I heard one person say, I wouldn't even be a Christian anymore if it weren't for my community group.

38:14.703 --> 38:19.610
I've heard stories in the last few months of community groups rallying to pay rent for someone who can't.

38:20.251 --> 38:25.618
Community groups rallying and sacrificing to care for one of their members in their community group who is ill.

38:26.338 --> 38:32.864
I mean, this is where we do the one another's, where we love one another, where we pray for one another, where we confess to one another.

38:33.986 --> 38:43.094
But while reality like community groups aren't there, I would say they're the primary way that we have structure for this as a church, it's not the only way to be in Christian community.

38:44.516 --> 38:54.866
Our hope for everyone, whether you can be in a formal community group or not, is that you would have intentional Christian community in your life and have rhythms that represent that.

38:55.874 --> 39:03.804
And so maybe it doesn't work for you schedule wise or whatever that is, but do you have people in your life that you're committed to doing the one another's with?

39:04.404 --> 39:05.265
So that was my first question.

39:05.526 --> 39:07.308
Who are you doing that one another's with?

39:07.688 --> 39:11.693
My second question is, when do you do the one another's with those people?

39:12.875 --> 39:13.796
So here's what I mean.

39:14.557 --> 39:19.863
Some of you have access to Christian community, but you don't have intentional rhythms of Christian community.

39:20.344 --> 39:25.490
So like, yeah, I could call someone if I needed to confess some sin, but that's not enough.

39:26.050 --> 39:31.518
Like you need rhythms in your life where you're committed to doing these one anothers.

39:32.480 --> 39:36.626
So when we talk about Christian community, it's not just hanging out with friends who are Christians.

39:36.646 --> 39:37.227
That's great.

39:37.327 --> 39:38.408
I hope we do that all the time.

39:39.049 --> 39:46.260
We're talking about intentional fellowship where we're getting together and saying, how are you really doing and praying for each other and doing these one anothers?

39:49.705 --> 39:55.794
I know that for some of you, I just wanna, I know

39:56.130 --> 40:03.780
I know that for some of you this is hard because there's wounds and you just feel like I'm too relationally broken.

40:05.061 --> 40:10.729
Like maybe you have wounds from your childhood or maybe it's from a church, but you think I just can't go there.

40:10.969 --> 40:18.319
Pastor, I'll show up for Sundays, but I'm too relationally broken to go there with a small group of people.

40:18.659 --> 40:19.340
Let me tell you a story.

40:21.483 --> 40:24.146
There's this tree that was planted by the city

40:24.226 --> 40:46.434
right around the corner from where I live and I walk by it almost every day when I'm walking my dog and One day I walk by and a a car had I don't know what happened But clearly a car had gotten out of control and and went into this person's front yard on the corner Demolish their metal fence.

40:46.454 --> 40:49.938
I mean like fences gone and this tree is

40:50.210 --> 40:54.035
was, I mean, it clearly went over, it hit the tree and went over it.

40:54.095 --> 40:58.501
So this tree was, you know, it might be six feet tall, like a year old, something, I don't know, the city planted it.

40:59.002 --> 41:00.845
And I mean, it demolished this tree.

41:01.205 --> 41:09.096
I mean, it was like the trunk of it was like cracked, where it was split, it was bent over, like over half the way.

41:09.116 --> 41:13.402
And I saw this tree and I thought, that tree is dead, like gone.

41:13.662 --> 41:15.465
No chance of any life in that tree.

41:16.105 --> 41:19.410
And I walk by it every day, still there.

41:19.618 --> 41:21.380
I walked by it.

41:21.520 --> 41:24.383
It seemed like it started to stand up a little bit more over time.

41:24.463 --> 41:30.910
It was still like cracked and just looked mangled, still assuming like there's no hope for this tree.

41:30.930 --> 41:42.242
And last week, I walk around the corner and I see this tree, this same tree filled with bright pink blossoms.

41:43.103 --> 41:46.066
It's called a pink trumpet tree.

41:46.210 --> 41:48.414
And they're called pink trumpets because that's what it looks like.

41:48.735 --> 41:51.459
And they're everywhere so bright that you could hardly imagine.

41:51.840 --> 41:56.328
And I see this tree filled with blossoms and I'm just utterly shocked.

41:56.869 --> 41:57.530
Like what?

41:58.232 --> 41:59.434
I thought this tree was dead.

41:59.494 --> 42:02.199
Like this tree had no chance of surviving.

42:02.459 --> 42:07.528
How in the world did it bear these blossoms, these beautiful things?

42:07.849 --> 42:10.674
And so I literally went and I like looked it up.

42:10.754 --> 42:12.056
What is this super tree?

42:12.116 --> 42:19.705
Does the city put some secret DNA in these trees to make them, were they going to recover from anything?

42:19.725 --> 42:23.750
And what I found in research was that no, it's a pink trumpet tree.

42:23.850 --> 42:29.316
It could survive something like this for some really basic reasons.

42:29.477 --> 42:31.779
One is because it has roots that go beneath the ground.

42:32.520 --> 42:35.263
And two, it kept getting sunlight and water.

42:35.524 --> 42:35.964
That's it.

42:36.785 --> 42:37.126
That's it.

42:37.927 --> 42:40.690
And look, some of you, you feel like that tree.

42:40.770 --> 42:47.099
Whatever's happened to you, you feel too relationally broken to be able to engage with community anymore.

42:47.700 --> 42:49.843
And I want to say there's hope with God.

42:51.065 --> 42:56.893
You can have roots beneath the surface with your relationship with God that can genuinely bear fruit.

42:57.534 --> 43:06.066
And you just need the constant basics, the sunshine of God's grace and the water of healthy relationships in your life.

43:06.978 --> 43:10.362
that can bring restoration and bare fruit in your life.

43:10.843 --> 43:12.565
So I just hope, I just wanna plead with you.

43:13.066 --> 43:15.869
Don't give up, there's always hope with God.

43:16.570 --> 43:24.520
And we've gotta lean into these practices of bearing with one another, forgiving one another, teaching one another, and admonishing one another.

43:26.042 --> 43:30.688
Next, this practice gives us seven postures to sustain real community.

43:30.748 --> 43:35.634
So these four practices are gonna cultivate it, these seven postures are gonna sustain it,

43:36.162 --> 43:37.163
Let me fly through these.

43:37.804 --> 43:39.466
First is compassion.

43:40.127 --> 43:42.290
So that means we enter into pain.

43:42.991 --> 43:44.813
We move towards hurting people.

43:45.033 --> 43:46.335
We mourn with those who mourn.

43:46.395 --> 43:48.037
We lead with compassion.

43:48.778 --> 43:50.080
Next is kindness.

43:50.921 --> 43:52.062
We respond with mercy.

43:52.242 --> 43:53.284
We don't retaliate.

43:53.744 --> 43:57.669
We respond to hate with love and we respond to harshness with gentleness.

43:58.510 --> 44:02.816
This is the posture that's going to sustain this real community.

44:03.577 --> 44:04.498
Next is humility.

44:04.866 --> 44:06.208
We don't always assume that we're right.

44:06.488 --> 44:10.054
In fact, we know that we're often wrong and that we have blind spots.

44:10.655 --> 44:12.157
And so we give the benefit of the doubt.

44:12.938 --> 44:15.622
We enter into community humbly.

44:16.484 --> 44:17.626
Next is meekness.

44:18.307 --> 44:19.388
We restrain power.

44:20.270 --> 44:22.152
And so meek doesn't mean weak.

44:22.854 --> 44:25.638
It actually means strength that's guided by love.

44:26.479 --> 44:30.585
It's a gentleness that comes from knowing that everyone is going through something.

44:32.328 --> 44:33.650
Next is patience.

44:33.954 --> 44:34.996
We stay when it's hard.

44:36.118 --> 44:38.862
The easy thing to do when things get difficult is to move on.

44:40.285 --> 44:43.270
But we're patient people by God's grace.

44:43.290 --> 44:43.831
We stay.

44:43.911 --> 44:47.637
We endure because we know that the grass isn't greener on the other side.

44:48.419 --> 44:51.804
And we don't just want to jump from shallow relationship to shallow relationship.

44:52.926 --> 44:54.609
And the next is love.

44:55.371 --> 44:57.394
We seek your good.

44:57.474 --> 44:58.155
at our cost.

44:58.195 --> 45:01.059
We seek the good of others at our own cost.

45:01.139 --> 45:03.101
And let me read verse 14 to you here.

45:03.522 --> 45:07.046
These last two postures here are the most important.

45:07.066 --> 45:14.396
It says, and above all these, put on love, which binds everything together in perfect harmony.

45:15.297 --> 45:22.886
So you have all these other postures, compassion, kindness, humility, meekness, patience, but love is what binds them all together.

45:22.986 --> 45:25.810
And it says in perfect harmony.

45:26.914 --> 45:30.819
You know, my, my daughters love to sing and they have beautiful voices.

45:31.120 --> 45:32.041
I love hearing them sing.

45:32.141 --> 45:38.089
And what they love, what they do is one person will sing the melody and the other three will harmonize.

45:39.031 --> 45:53.130
And so what that means is, is that they pick different notes than the melody, but that go with that note so that they all blend together to make a fuller, richer sound than they could make one by themselves.

45:54.171 --> 45:56.114
That's what it means to harmonize.

45:56.386 --> 45:59.429
Well, we believe that Jesus is the melody.

45:59.990 --> 46:03.053
His life is a beautiful song of redemption.

46:03.753 --> 46:06.917
And when we love one another, we're harmonizing.

46:07.677 --> 46:21.912
When we love one another in service, in sacrifice, in care, in forgiveness, our lives are playing different notes that blend together to make a fuller, richer community to the glory of God.

46:22.692 --> 46:24.274
And so we need love.

46:24.354 --> 46:26.177
at the core of our community.

46:26.497 --> 46:28.520
And then lastly, there's peace.

46:29.341 --> 46:30.983
We submit to Christ's rule.

46:31.404 --> 46:36.952
Now, the peace that it's talking about here is not an inner calm, but relational wholeness.

46:38.254 --> 46:39.475
It's talking about the body of Christ.

46:39.936 --> 46:42.580
And he says, let the peace of Christ rule in your hearts.

46:42.620 --> 46:47.026
And the word rule there could literally be like moderate or even referee.

46:47.650 --> 46:54.618
So conflict is resolved, not by one person winning or losing, but by mutually submitting to Christ through His word.

46:56.099 --> 46:58.442
Let the peace of Christ rule in your hearts.

47:00.584 --> 47:05.750
I gotta say something really important about these seven postures.

47:06.551 --> 47:07.832
Some of you are gonna hear me.

47:07.892 --> 47:11.196
You're gonna hear these seven things as seven shoulds.

47:12.498 --> 47:14.159
You should be more compassionate.

47:14.980 --> 47:16.562
You should be more kind.

47:17.186 --> 47:19.790
You should be more meek.

47:19.810 --> 47:23.475
And that some of you, that's the only way that you know how to, to receive things.

47:23.495 --> 47:24.857
That's not what I'm saying.

47:25.278 --> 47:26.920
That's not what this is saying.

47:27.681 --> 47:36.033
Remember what I said at the beginning that what's happening in this passage is you've been risen with Christ, put off the old self, put on the new self.

47:37.014 --> 47:40.780
And then this is showing us what the new self in Christ is.

47:41.000 --> 47:42.823
Your life is hidden with Christ.

47:43.243 --> 47:45.266
You're clothed in Christ.

47:45.602 --> 47:49.286
So it's not saying be more compassionate, be more kind, be more humble.

47:49.566 --> 47:52.910
It is saying this is who you are in Christ.

47:53.511 --> 47:56.715
And this is why it's possible for you to experience this in community.

47:57.575 --> 48:03.602
So just imagine with me for a second that I know some of you are into design, fashion.

48:03.662 --> 48:10.009
Imagine walking in to a really well-known fashion designer's wardrobe.

48:10.971 --> 48:14.034
Like you walk into your dream wardrobe, okay?

48:14.498 --> 48:18.403
You're like, here's the shoes, here's the handbags, here's the jackets.

48:19.765 --> 48:21.046
You're seeing all this stuff.

48:21.066 --> 48:27.454
You're just in heaven, imagining all of this, and you get to pick and choose all these different things and walk out wearing all of that.

48:28.075 --> 48:33.822
What this passage is saying is that every morning you get to walk into the wardrobe of Christ.

48:35.084 --> 48:40.050
And so you're not just putting on compassion, you're putting on Christ's compassion.

48:40.450 --> 48:47.137
You're putting on Christ's kindness, Christ's humility, his meekness, his patience, his love, his peace.

48:47.217 --> 48:49.460
You are clothed in Christ.

48:49.940 --> 48:51.622
That's why community is possible.

48:54.925 --> 48:59.530
And so I've tried to show you a beautifully difficult and messy vision of community.

49:00.591 --> 49:06.898
And let me just close by saying what I said towards the beginning of, don't idealize what I'm saying to you even now.

49:07.234 --> 49:12.921
Okay, some of you are like, I'm gonna embrace messy community, community perfectly, okay?

49:13.922 --> 49:15.104
Relax, okay?

49:15.825 --> 49:19.349
Some of you are like, I'm gonna go sign up for a community group and it's gonna be amazing.

49:19.910 --> 49:21.332
Maybe, I'm gonna mite.

49:23.074 --> 49:26.278
It might also take a while to really connect and get to know other people.

49:26.759 --> 49:29.082
So don't idealize what I'm saying to you.

49:29.122 --> 49:29.903
Here's what I want you to do.

49:30.423 --> 49:35.730
Acknowledge the difficulty and the slow grind of building real community.

49:36.194 --> 49:37.696
And then take one practical step.

49:38.016 --> 49:39.858
Today, take one practical step.

49:39.898 --> 49:40.919
Let me give you four options.

49:41.680 --> 49:44.242
One practical step is that you could join a community group.

49:44.262 --> 49:48.426
We're gonna have a table set up in the courtyard where you can talk to some of our community groups team about that.

49:48.587 --> 49:51.830
Maybe today's the day that you join a community group.

49:51.890 --> 49:53.291
Second, a practical step.

49:54.172 --> 49:56.935
Schedule a regular time with a Christian friend for a check-in.

49:57.556 --> 50:03.762
Hey, once a week, once a month, whatever it is, let's get together or talk on the phone at this time

50:03.906 --> 50:05.448
And let's check in on each other.

50:05.488 --> 50:06.009
How are you doing?

50:06.029 --> 50:09.014
This is our time to confess to one another, pray for one another to do that.

50:09.034 --> 50:10.977
Just schedule a time with one other Christian friend.

50:11.858 --> 50:17.586
A third practical thing that you could do in light of this is pursue someone who might not have community.

50:18.488 --> 50:25.338
Maybe you're hearing this and you're yesterday, minting everything I'm saying today and you are walking in community and you are just so grateful to God for that in your life.

50:26.059 --> 50:30.706
But maybe the practical step for you is to pursue others who don't have that and invite them in.

50:31.394 --> 50:35.639
And then fourth, seriously, if all of those things are like, man, I don't know if I can commit, just pray.

50:36.260 --> 50:37.041
Talk to God about it.

50:37.702 --> 50:42.168
Whatever's going on in your heart right now, bring it to the Lord and ask Him.

50:42.949 --> 50:43.629
Okay, pray.

50:44.771 --> 50:53.662
I simply want to close by reading the final verse in this, says, whatever you do in word or deed, do everything in the name of the Lord Jesus, giving thanks to God the Father through Him.

50:54.623 --> 50:56.786
So at the end of the day, it's not about us.

50:57.666 --> 50:59.328
Community doesn't exist for itself.

50:59.548 --> 51:02.892
It's all because of the gospel and for the glory of God.

51:03.593 --> 51:10.721
We are redeemed into this community and we don't exist for ourselves, but for God's mission and for his glory.

51:10.741 --> 51:18.770
And so my hope for us is that we would walk with one another, but we would do so with hands lifted high to the glory of God.

51:19.250 --> 51:24.956
Because he's the one who not only has called us to himself, but who has adopted us into his family.

51:25.297 --> 51:26.418
Pray with me.

51:26.530 --> 51:30.657
God, we thank you so much for the gift of community.

51:30.817 --> 51:37.428
It truly is a privilege to be a part of a family with brothers and sisters.

51:38.610 --> 51:43.898
But God, we also pray that we would see that this gift is a responsibility and that it's not easy.

51:43.918 --> 51:53.714
Would you give us biblical expectations for community, knowing that it's going to take sacrifice, it's going to take time, it's going to take work,

51:54.274 --> 51:56.517
And yet you're gonna be at work in the midst of it all.

51:57.318 --> 52:04.408
And so Father, would you help us to be a people who let the word of Christ dwell in us richly, teaching and admonishing one another.

52:04.929 --> 52:07.552
And when we fall short, forgiving one another.

52:08.033 --> 52:14.822
And over time, bearing with one another, that we might experience your grace in the tangible form of relationships.

52:15.403 --> 52:16.624
We pray this in Jesus' name.

52:17.025 --> 52:17.345
Amen.

52:17.866 --> 52:18.046
Amen.

52:19.689 --> 52:20.690
Thank you for listening.

52:21.026 --> 52:25.362
For more audio and video content, please visit realityla.com.

